====Freshman====
On November 18, 2005, in an 84<U+2013>56 defeat of [[Southern Jaguars|Southern University]], Rolle made his collegiate debut, playing 14 minutes and scoring six points while also grabbing three rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/boxscore?gameId=253220099|title=Southern University Jaguars vs. LSU Tigers -- Box Score|work=[[ESPN]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=November 18, 2005|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref> Rolle's season high in rebounds (10) and points (8) while shooting 4-of-8 from the field helped lead LSU past [[Nicholls State University|Nicholls State]] on November 21. He equaled his season high in points against the [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt Commodores]] on February 2, 2006, in only nine minutes of playing time.<ref name=LSU/> The Tigers' surprised many with a [[Final Four]] run, and in that game Rolle led the team in rebounds with eight, recorded two points from 1-of-1 shooting, and blocked a shot, all in 14 minutes of playing time. Despite this performance, LSU's opponent [[2005<U+2013>06 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|UCLA]] ultimately prevailed, 59<U+2013>45.<ref>{{cite news|first=Fred|last=Sturrup|url=http://www.jonesbahamas.com/?c=123&a=8304|title=Magnum Rolle Comes Of Age!|work=[[The Bahama Journal]]|date=April 3, 2006|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref> Over the course of the [[2005-06 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2005<U+2013>06 season]], Rolle averaged 2.2 points, 2.5 rebounds, and 8.7 minutes per game as a freshman, picking up 21 blocks on the year.<ref name=LSU/>

====Sophomore====
Coming into the [[2006-07 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2006<U+2013>07 season]], the Tigers returned four starters, including [[Glen Davis (basketball)|Glen "Big Baby" Davis]], and LSU fans hoped that Rolle would replace the shot blocking of [[Tyrus Thomas]]. As such, [[Andy Katz]] of ESPN named them the fifth best team in the nation in the preseason.<ref>{{cite web|first=Andy|last=Katz|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/news/story?id=2491073|title=ESPN.com 2006-07 June Top 25 (1-10)|work=[[ESPN]]|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|date=June 19, 2006|accessdate=July 1, 2010}}</ref> Rolle's averages improved slightly to 4.0 points, 4.1 rebounds, and 16.7 minutes per contest, with nine starts and 31 blocks. He had a season-best nine rebounds against [[Tulane Green Wave|Tulane]] on December 22, and recorded his first double-digit scoring night against the [[Tennessee Volunteers men's basketball|Tennessee Volunteers]] on March 8, 2007 in the [[2007 SEC Men's Basketball Tournament|SEC Tournament]], when he shot 5-for-7 from the field in 18 minutes for 10 points.<ref name=LSU/> However, two [[herniated disc]]s in his back impeded further progress.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jim|last=Kleinpeter|url=http://www.nola.com/sports/t-p/index.ssf?/base/sports-27/1166856581244330.xml&coll=1|title=Brady calls for more frontcourt production|work=[[The Times-Picayune]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|date=December 23, 2006|accessdate=July 2, 2010}}</ref> The Tigers finished the year 17<U+2013>15 and 5<U+2013>11 in SEC play, disappointing considering their preseason projection.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nba&id=3237084|title=Brady fired as LSU basketball coach|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=February 8, 2008|accessdate=July 23, 2010}}</ref>

Rolle decided to leave the LSU program on May 23. LSU coach [[John Brady (basketball)|John Brady]] claimed this was due to concerns over Rolle's development.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/mensbasketball/2007-05-23-3248855651_x.htm|title=Magnum Rolle leaves LSU|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=May 23, 2007|accessdate=July 23, 2010}}</ref> Former high school coach Darrel Sears said Rolle was unhappy with LSU since December 2006, and Brady had been making snide comments for a while. After Rolle left LSU, he was courted by Division I schools [[Wyoming Cowboys basketball|Wyoming]], [[Marshall Thundering Herd men's basketball|Marshall]], [[Oral Roberts Golden Eagles men's basketball|Oral Roberts]], [[University of Delaware|Delaware]], [[Louisiana Tech Bulldogs basketball|Louisiana Tech]], and [[South Florida Bulls|South Florida]]. Although initially interested in South Florida due to its proximity to his Bahamas home,<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Coakley|url=http://freeport.nassauguardian.net/sports/289076362910115.php|title=Coach Sears blasts back at Brady of LSU |work=[[The Freeport News]]|date=June 8, 2007|accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> Rolle chose to transfer to Louisiana Tech to play under [[Kerry Rupp]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jim|last=Kleinpeter|url=http://www.nola.com/sports/t-p/index.ssf?/base/sports-31/1181887054144120.xml&coll=1|title=Former Tigers headed to Tech|work=[[The Times-Picayune]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications]]|date=June 15, 2007|accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref>

===Louisiana Tech===
====Junior====
Rolle was forced to [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] the [[2007-08 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2007<U+2013>08 season]] due to transfer rules. In his first game as a [[Louisiana Tech Bulldogs basketball|Bulldog]], on November 15, 2008, he registered nine rebounds and eight points, including four consecutive points within the last minute, to propel Louisiana Tech past [[Louisiana-Lafayette]], 61<U+2013>59.<ref>{{cite news|first=Barbara|last=Walkin|url=http://freeport.nassauguardian.net/sports/293378236245292.php|title=Magnum returns to basketball in dramatic fashion |work=[[The Freeport News]]|date=November 20, 2008|accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> Rolle's first [[double-double]] came against [[Grambling State]] on November 18, with 12 points and 14 rebounds.<ref name=NBAProspect>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pacers/news/magnum_rolle_2010.html|title=Pacers: Prospect Profile 2010: Magnum Rolle|work=[[NBA]]|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> He led the team in scoring with a then-career high of 17 points in a [[blowout (sports)|blowout]] 78<U+2013>55 loss to #10 [[2008-09 UCLA Bruins men's basketball team|UCLA]] on December 28, while also contributing seven rebounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=283630026|title=No. 10 UCLA too much for Louisiana Tech|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=December 28, 2008|accessdate=July 23, 2010}}</ref> On January 29, 2009, Rolle had a perfect night from the field, shooting 11-for-11 with 23 points.<ref name=NBAProspect/> In a 60<U+2013>52 defeat at the hands of [[Utah State]] on February 7, Rolle badly fell on his hip early in the game, but he came back later to finish with eight points.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=290380328|title=Utah State holds off Louisiana Tech for victory|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=February 7, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref> He had a season high 25 points to go along with 11 rebounds and four blocked shots in leading the Bulldogs to a victory over [[Murray State]] 69<U+2013>60 on February 21.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=290530093|title=Louisiana Tech 69, Murray St. 60|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=February 21, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref> The next game, an 80<U+2013>71 win over [[New Mexico State]], Rolle equalled his season high in points (25) and grabbed 12 rebounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=290572348|title=Louisiana Tech 80, New Mexico St. 71|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=February 26, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>

Over the course of the [[2008-09 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2008<U+2013>09 season]], Rolle started 30 games for the Bulldogs and averaged 12.2 points, 7.2 rebounds, and 1.7 blocks per game. He registered five double-doubles while scoring in excess of 10 points on 18 occasions. Following the season, Rolle was named to the All-[[Western Athletic Conference|WAC]] Defensive Team and All-WAC Newcomer Team.<ref name=NBAProspect/> In addition, the Louisiana Sports Writers Association recognized Rolle as a member of the All-Louisiana third teams. Louisiana Tech teammate Kyle Gibson was named to its first team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latechsports.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/041209aaa.html|title=Gibson and Rolle Named All-LSWA |work=[[Louisiana Tech Bulldogs]]|publisher=[[Louisiana Tech University]]|date=April 12, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>

Rolle briefly flirted the [[2009 NBA Draft]]. He declared for early entry in the draft, but did not hire an [[sports agent|agent]].<ref>{{cite news|title=New Mexico State shooting guard Jonathan Gibson declares early entry for NBA draft|work=[[Las Cruces Sun-News]]|publisher=MediaNews Group|date=May 1, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref> After talking to NBA spokespeople who said he was a borderline second round selection, Rolle considered staying in college an extra year to earn a degree. He eventually pulled his name out of the draft, thus ensuring his college eligibility.<ref name=destiny/>

====Senior====
The WAC preseason polls were released on October 29, and Louisiana Tech was pegged to finish sixth in the media poll<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wacsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=45988&SPID=4126&DB_OEM_ID=10100&ATCLID=204817314|title=WAC Men's Basketball Preseason Media Picks Announced|work=[[Western Athletic Conference]]|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref> and fifth in the coaches poll. Fellow senior Gibson was named to the preseason All-WAC second team, but Rolle was not honored by any preseason award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wacsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=45988&SPID=4126&DB_OEM_ID=10100&ATCLID=204817383|title=WAC Announces Men's Basketball Coaches Preseason Picks |work=[[Western Athletic Conference]]|date=October 29, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref> In the Bulldogs' home opener against [[UALR]], Rolle was the leader in scoring with 23 points in crushing the Trojans 86<U+2013>66. Gibson and Olu Ashaolu also scored more than 20 points to push Louisiana Tech to a 4<U+2013>1 start, their best since 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=293292348|title=Louisiana Tech 86, Ark.-Little Rock 66|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=November 25, 2009|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref> Rolle's career high in points was 29, scored against [[University of Houston|Houston]] in a December 29 99<U+2013>94 defeat of the Cougars in which he also grabbed 10 boards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=293640248|title=Louisiana Tech 99, Houston 94|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=December 29, 2009|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> In the semifinal of the [[2010 WAC Men's Basketball Tournament|WAC tournament]], against the #1 seeded [[Utah State Aggies]], Rolle injured his ankle less than three minutes into the game, a factor in the Bulldogs' 30-point loss. They finished the regular season 23<U+2013>10, including a 9<U+2013>7 record in conference.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=300710328|title=Utah St. 85, Louisiana Tech 55|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=March 12, 2010|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> That was good enough for an invite to the [[2010 CollegeInsider.com Tournament]], in which Louisiana Tech defeated [[Southern Miss]] in the first round despite missing Rolle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegeinsider.com/tournament/2010_game8.html|title=Louisiana Tech Beats Southern Miss|work=CollegeInsider.com|date=March 18, 2010|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> In Rolle's final collegiate game, he contributed nine points off the bench despite a 69<U+2013>40 rout of the Bulldogs by [[Missouri State]] in the CIT's quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collegeinsider.com/tournament/2010_game11.html|title=Missouri State runs past Louisiana Tech|work=CollegeInsider.com|date=March 22, 2010|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref>

During the [[2009-10 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2009<U+2013>10 season]], Rolle started 33 games, 24 of which he scored in double figures and 11 of which were double-doubles. He rejected more shots than anyone else in the WAC, averaging 2.1 blocks per game, and finished fourth in career blocked shots at Louisiana Tech despite playing there for only two seasons.<ref name=NBAProspect/> Rolle also posted averages of 8.4 rebounds per game, third in the WAC (behind [[Luke Babbitt]] of [[University of Nevada-Reno|Nevada]] and Chis Oakes of [[San Jose State]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/stats/leaders/WAC/REBAVG/regularseason/yearly|title=NCAA Basketball Stats - WAC Leaders in Rebounds Per Game|work=[[CBS Sports]]|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> and 13.9 points per game, twelfth in the WAC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/stats/leaders/WAC/PTSAVG/regularseason/yearly|title=NCAA Basketball Stats - WAC Leaders in Points Per Game|work=[[CBS Sports]]|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> His field goal percentage was 51.1%, tied with Babbitt for third in conference and behind Tai Wesley of Utah State and Ike Okoye of [[Boise State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/stats/leaders/WAC/FGPCT/regularseason/yearly|title=NCAA Basketball Stats - WAC Leaders in Field Goal Percentage|work=[[CBS Sports]]|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> At the conclusion of the season, Rolle was named to the Lefty Driesell All-America Defensive Team, All-WAC Defensive Team, All-WAC Second Team, and All-Louisiana Second Team.<ref name=NBAProspect/> He graduated from Louisiana Tech with a bachelor's degree in [[sociology]] in March 2010, becoming the first person in his family to earn a degree.<ref name=destiny/>

==NBA career==
===2010 NBA Draft===
Prior to the [[2010 NBA Draft]], Rolle hired [[Fletcher Cockrell]] to be his agent.<ref name=LAScout>{{cite news|url=http://louisianatech.scout.com/2/980030.html|title=Rolle Taken by Indiana In NBA Draft |work=[[Scout.com]]|publisher=[[Fox Sports]]|date=June 25, 2010|accessdate=June 30, 2010}}</ref> [[ESPN]], NBADraft.net, and DraftExpress.com projected him to be a possible mid-to-late second round selection. He worked out with NBA teams the [[Washington Wizards]], [[Phoenix Suns]], [[Milwaukee Bucks]], [[Charlotte Bobcats]], and [[Indiana Pacers]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Renaldo|last=Dorsett|url=http://www.tribune242.com/sports/06232010_ROLLE-DRAFT_sport|title=Magnum enters 64th NBA Draft |work=[[The Bahamas Tribune]]|date=June 23, 2010|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref> Dave-Te' Thomas of [[CBS Sports]] said that Rolle had a good wingspan and was very athletic. He added while larger NBA forwards might push him around, he was an intense player and would not back down if challenged. Thomas compared Rolle to former LSU teammate [[Tyrus Thomas]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Dave Te'|last=Thomas |url=http://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/stats/leaders/WAC/FGPCT/regularseason/yearly|title=Magnum Rolle, Louisiana Tech, 2010 NBA Draft|work=[[CBS Sports]]|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref>

In the 2010 NBA Draft, Rolle was chosen with the 21st pick of the second round and 51st overall by the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]].<ref name=NBAProspect/> His rights were traded to the Pacers for [[Ryan Reid]], who was the 57th overall pick, along with undisclosed cash considerations.<ref>{{cite news|first=Cliff|last=Brunt|url=http://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/2010-06-25-1239744670_x.htm|title=Pacers acquire Rolle in 2nd round|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=June 25, 2010|accessdate=September 6, 2010}}</ref> Rolle was the first NBA player drafted out of Louisiana Tech since [[Paul Millsap]] was picked by the [[Utah Jazz]] with the 47th pick of the [[2006 NBA Draft]].<ref name=LAScout/> In addition, he was the first [[Grand Bahama]]ian selected in the draft ever. Bahamas Minister of Youth Sports and Culture [[Charles Maynard]] and Minister of Works and Transport [[Neko C Grant]] congratulated Rolle on his historic achievement.<ref name=MinCongrat/>

===2010 NBA Summer League===
{{quote box |width=350px|margin=15px|align = right |qalign = right |bgcolor = #c6dbf7
|quote = He's been by far the best player by a large margin (in camp). He has dominated everything. He has scored. He has rebounded. He has defended well. He has a surprisingly high basketball IQ. He shoots really well and pursues every offensive rebound.|source =&nbsp;<U+2014> Indiana Pacers coach [[Jim O'Brien]], speaking of Magnum Rolle<ref name=Bird>{{cite news|first=Fred|last=Sturrup|url=http://freeport.nassauguardian.net/sports/65099920161089.php|title=Larry Bird/Magnum Rolle connection|work=[[The Freeport News]]|date=July 21, 2010|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref>}}

He played well in the 2010 [[Orlando Summer League]], garnering averages of 28 minutes, 13.4 points, seven rebounds, and two blocked shots per game. On opening day of the summer league, the Pacers beat the [[Orlando Magic]] 86<U+2013>77 behind Rolle's 13 points, five rebounds, two blocks, and a steal. In the second game, an 80<U+2013>69 loss to the [[New Jersey Nets]], Rolle scored nine points, brought down three rebounds, and rejected three shots. Against the [[Utah Jazz]], Rolle's 10 points, eight rebounds, and four blocks facilitated an 83<U+2013>74 Pacers win. The fourth game, which [[The Bahamas Tribune]] said was the most thrilling of the summer league, featured a 27-point deficit erased by Indiana for a comeback win over the [[Boston Celtics]]. Rolle had a double-double, with 19 points and 11 boards. The Pacers and him wrapped up the Orlando Summer League with a 77<U+2013>73 defeat by the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]], in which Rolle posted 16 points, eight rebounds and two blocks.<ref>{{cite news|first=Renaldo|last=Dorsett|url=http://www.tribune242.com/sports/07132010_Rolle_Sports|title=Magnum Rolle edges nearer NBA dream |work=[[The Bahamas Tribune]]|date=July 13, 2010|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref>

===Indiana Pacers===
Following his strong performances at the Orlando Summer League, Rolle, along with fellow Pacer rookie [[Lance Stephenson]], was named one of the "steals of the draft" by the [[Boston Globe]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Gary|last=Washburn|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/articles/2010/07/25/pacers_banking_on_big_moves_next_summer/|title=Pacers banking on big moves next summer|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |date=July 25, 2010|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> Rolle was invited to the Pacers' training camp, where he injured his head, requiring stitches.<ref name=Bird/> Although he has not been signed yet, Pacers owner [[Larry Bird]] mentioned the team wished to retain Rolle.<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Coakley|url=http://freeport.nassauguardian.net/sports/4808077029613.php|title=Larry Bird: 'we want to keep Magnum' |work=[[The Freeport News]]|date=August 21, 2010|accessdate=August 26, 2010}}</ref>

